RACHEL STRUGATZ ( https://puck.news/author/rachel-strugatz/?utm_campaign=3D=
Line+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F21%2F24%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%287%2F19%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io=
&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

The week got off to a frenzied start on Monday morning when I learned that =
Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies C.E.O. Fabrizio Freda would finally be stepping=
 down at the end of this fiscal year. Ahead of its full year earnings and a=
 depressing 2025 outlook, ELC announced that Freda had at last informed the=
 board of his =E2=80=9Cintention to retire,=E2=80=9D which comes just two m=
onths after longtime and well-regarded C.F.O Tracey Travis also decided to =
retire. Afterward, I heard about two more yet-to-be announced high-ranking =
departures, both of whom are on the ELC executive leadership team: Mark Loo=
mis, group president of North America, and Peter Jueptner, group president =
of International. (A spokesperson for The Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies decli=
ned to comment.)

That=E2=80=99s a lot of executive
turnover for a company whose board has long insisted, as recently as June, =
that Freda wasn=E2=80=99t going anywhere. A person close to the situation t=
old me that Fabrizio =E2=80=9Cmade the decision to announce his retirement =
and then informed the board.=E2=80=9D But reading between the lines of the =
curiously-worded announcement from Lauder, it sure sounds like Freda capitu=
lated to the board, and not the other way around.

