Indeed, it=E2=80=99s hard not to see Freda=E2=80=99s accelerated retirement=
 as the board=E2=80=99s trauma response to ELC=E2=80=99s share prices dippi=
ng below $100 for the first time since 2017. =E2=80=9CI think they were goi=
ng to give him a chance to turn it around, but it was untenable,=E2=80=9D a=
 former company executive said. Another source close to the Lauder family r=
emarked that they =E2=80=9Ccouldn=E2=80=99t get a fix on the revenue and pr=
ofitability of the company. There was no turnaround.=E2=80=9D The last stra=
w, this person continued, was =E2=80=9Cwhen they were going to preview the =
earnings call and realized that next year was not going to make forecasts.=
=E2=80=9D

The timing of Freda=E2=80=99s exit came as a genuine shock inside the compa=
ny. =E2=80=9CIt was much earlier than the company seemed to indicate just a=
 few months ago, and that was a surprise,=E2=80=9D a person with ties to se=
nior leadership told me.
=E2=80=9CNo one knew it was coming,=E2=80=9D said the source close to the f=
amily. According to an Est=C3=A9e insider, the timeline might have been dif=
ferent had the company not been forced to lower its forecasts. =E2=80=9CThe=
y had no choice but to do it before the earnings in order to keep confidenc=
e that they were making changes,=E2=80=9D this person said, referring to Mo=
nday=E2=80=99s dismal quarterly call, when Lauder reported that net sales h=
ad dipped 2 percent from the previous year; that skin care and makeup reven=
ues declined by 3 percent and 1 percent, respectively; and warned that Chin=
a and travel retail continue to pose serious challenges to its business.

Of course, there was never any doubt that Freda would be leaving, at some p=
oint soon. This was the last official year of Freda=E2=80=99s current incen=
tive package with the company, where he needed to remain C.E.O. until June =
30, the end of Lauder=E2=80=99s fiscal 2024, to make his numbers. =E2=80=9C=
At any other company, Fabrizio would have been gone
by now,=E2=80=9D a Lauder executive told me ( https://puck.news/whats-behin=
d-estee-lauder-cfo-tracey-travis-retirement/?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SU=
BSCRIBERS+%288%2F21%2F24%29&utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F1=
9%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c=
60617da42abd12a ) back in July. Four weeks later, he was on his way.

The Succession Question

The Lauder family, which owns 38 percent of the ELC common stock and 86 per=
cent of the voting stock, could hand Freda=E2=80=99s job to a family member=
, too. Internally, everyone is talking about Jane Lauder, the company=E2=80=
=99s chief data officer and executive V.P. of enterprise marketing, who not=
 only wants to be C.E.O., but appears to have the support of her father, Ro=
nald Lauder, as well as his older brother Leonard, the chairman emeritus. S=
ome think it may be a shorter =E2=80=9Ctransition=E2=80=9D than people thin=
k, with a potential announcement that could be timed to the annual stockhol=
ders meeting in November.

Current senior employees are also saying that succession planning in the ne=
ar term could be centered around a dual-C.E.O. strategy, starring Jane Laud=
er and St=C3=A9phane De La Faverie, an executive group
president, which presents an interesting opportunity for the executives to =
prove themselves. =E2=80=9CThe thought is to have a person representing the=
 family and a person who is thought to have more of Fabrizio=E2=80=99s thin=
king,=E2=80=9D said a person with ties to the company, who called a dual-C.=
E.O. path a compromise=C2=AD=C2=AD=E2=80=93=E2=80=93and a test. Already, Ja=
ne and de La Faverie are working together closely. Tracey Travis=E2=80=99s =
internal memo from July, detailing the =E2=80=9CProfit Recovery and Growth =
Plan,=E2=80=9D said that the initiative would be led by Jane and de la Fave=
rie.

