          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The week got off to=
 a <i>frenzied</i> start on Monday morning when I learned that Est=C3=A9e L=
auder Companies C.E.O. <b>Fabrizio</b> <b>Freda</b> would finally be steppi=
ng down at the end of this fiscal year. Ahead of its full year earnings and=
 a depressing 2025 outlook, ELC announced that Freda had at last informed t=
he board of his =E2=80=9Cintention to retire,=E2=80=9D which comes just two=
 months after longtime and well-regarded C.F.O <b>Tracey</b> <b>Travis</b> =
also <i>decided to retire</i>. Afterward, I heard about two more yet-to-be =
announced high-ranking departures, both of whom are on the ELC executive le=
adership team: <b>Mark</b> <b>Loomis</b>, group president of North America,=
 and <b>Peter</b> <b>Jueptner</b>, group president of International. (A spo=
kesperson for The Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies declined to comment.)<br/><br=
/>That=E2=80=99s a lot of executive
turnover for a company whose board has long insisted, as recently as June, =
that Freda wasn=E2=80=99t going anywhere. A person close to the situation t=
old me that Fabrizio =E2=80=9Cmade the decision to announce his retirement =
and then informed the board.=E2=80=9D But reading between the lines of the =
curiously-worded announcement from Lauder, it sure sounds like Freda capitu=
lated to the board, and not the other way around. <br/></td>
         </tr>
